segments.text: And I don't think that, I really don't think there should be any classes that size.
I could see it maybe having a very distinguished lecture and then having a whole bunch of teaching assistants take them into separate sections, but that's not the way it happens there.
They're in a class of 500 and then they have stanton tests.
More money needs to go into faculty and less into building.
We spend all our money on building.
I was very glad to see a couple of years ago, was it last year, that somebody decided simply that the money would do with the faculty would not go anywhere else.
I want to see more if it's a place on teaching as something to be evaluated in children and families in case it falls off the board.
I want to see fewer committees and less committee work because I think the people now in the community are so involved in committee work that we don't have time to teach.
I'd like to see sabbatical given more regularly and without competition.
Because I think it should be the case that somebody was doing a good job for X number of years deserves a sabbatical.
Things that would affect the whole institution.
How about the enrollment?
Yeah, I was just going to raise that issue.
An admission report.
I think that they should cap the enrollment.
They already have that, haven't they?
I think they have.
Let's say they have.
Raise the admission requirements.
And encourage rather than discourage out-of-state.
We're not going to have thousands and thousands of people walking in if we do that.
We make it a little more open to people from Pennsylvania, California.
I think too that we should work with junior college systems.
And we are doing some of that.
I know that we work with Glenn to alleviate the pressure on pressure.
And this is good.
What is your finding so far about the quality of the instruction that Glenn is giving?
Well, on the basic level, it's pretty much the same.
And they're all our graduate students who are teaching here who are also teaching there.
Who then, in some cases, graduate
their masters and go teach there full-time, often because they're married to somebody here.
I don't think there's any problem with that.
They have worse students.
They've got some awful students over there.
And sometimes the awful students will get through the courses just because anybody who does all the work over there is going to get through.
Nobody's going to fail except people who disappear at midterm.
So we do get some people from Blinn that have high grades that aren't very
But I don't think that they're getting bad courses over there.
I think they're getting good courses.
And, in fact, I think they're getting essentially our courses.
How do you feel?
What is your thought about A&M's future?
Is it optimistic, pessimistic, or...
Well, it's optimistic, but I do think that we have to cap enrollment if we haven't already done it and really should reduce it some.
It should go down to, oh, I'd say no more than 35.
I don't know how to do this.
This is not, but it would seem to be possible to do it.
What about Region 2020?
What do you think is that?
I think a lot of it is meanness.
I read a lot of that document, and I thought, God.
Some of it is very good, but a lot of it is very vague, too.
I mean, we really need to have more constructors on all levels.
And we need to have, to be competitive with you too, we need to have a lot more structures.
And that's in the report, but it's not specific enough.
I'm using the word instructor, meaning anyone who teaches.
But I don't think that we can do it with, for a while we had many, many lectures.
I don't think this is a good idea, because people who are really good,
We have a couple of lifetime lectures who are excellent.
But we've had many, many people pass through here, some of whom were terrible.
So I think we need more tenure-track people.
And those lectures we do have, we need to treat well, and we need to make them senior lecturers so that somebody, for instance, like Dorothy Van Ryber, have you spoken with her?
No, no, I've done Paul.
I haven't done Dorothy.
Yeah, okay.
Well, she's a lifetime lecturer.
And she will tell you what this does.
Because she's teaching essential classes.
And yet I think that there's a kind of bitterness on the part of lifetime lectures because they're not, and she is a senior lecturer, but we need to have better conditions for our lecturers.
All right.
Any female-related experiences, plus and minus, that you want to share that we haven't already done throughout all the years?
Female-related?
Yeah.
Okay.
Being a woman faculty member, the pluses or the minuses here?
Well, I can think of lots of little slights from the old days, but nothing major.
What about a positive where you go, okay, the thing has turned.
The tide is going the positive way.
Being a female, I don't know.
I do remember that when I was having children, my students did not approve of this.
And one of them said to me, this is a negative experience, a core person said to me, I wouldn't let my wife be pregnant and teach.
Here I was about eight months pregnant and I was teaching.
And I don't remember what I said to him.
I remember I looked at him in astonishment, but I don't remember, I don't think I had any snappy come back.
I think I just said, well, that's lovely for you, and went on to something else.
I encountered that quite a bit and it was kind of funny because there were a bunch of pregnant teachers in the English department at once.

Pat Harris was in the department then and she was pregnant and there was a woman named Judy Finn who hasn't been around for years and years and she was there and we kind of took up the whole faculty room.
But there was a certain amount of you shouldn't be here at that point that was not accepted.
I can't think of any really awful
I never encountered, nor can I think of anything astoundingly wonderful that happened to me here because I was a woman.
I've just always been here and I've always taught.
I've become aware of the improvement of attitudes towards women.
And as the years go by, there are more and more women.
There's less and less discrimination against them.
But there are still some Aggies who
If we could get all of the people from your A&M experience into one place, to which ones and for what would you most want to express your appreciation?
Okay, Stanley Archer.
Because?
Because he guided me all these years.
He was one of the first people to recognize me as a faculty member as opposed to another one of the teaching assistants.
Frank Pierce, because actually Frank was very protective during those years.
And he was one of the people that, for instance, back then you didn't have any choice about where and when you talk ordinarily.
And they could just as soon send you a mile away.
But Frank Pierce was always, like when I was having children and so forth, he always made sure my classes were relatively local and that they were at good hours.
And he also, he was the first person to say, we all, I called all these people, doctor this and that.
And Frank was the first person to say, call me Frank.
And I appreciated that.
Okay, Stanley Frank.
Bedford Clark, but just he's my long-term friend here.
I was here when they hired him.
I think he was a great hire.
He's always been around for good advice.
Who else?
Don't have to be in the department now.
Anyone?
Oh, they don't have to be in the department.
Anyone associated with A&M that you...
Okay, Maxine Davenport, Manuel's first wife, and Manuel himself.
Sylvia Grider, who also came in a long time ago and who has not been treated well by the system.
His name comes to mind always when I think it's people not being treated well.
An odd name that you may not even remember.
Do you remember Parks Hunter?
Well, he caused everybody much food, but he was very kind to me and very helpful.
And he made all kinds of dreadful mistakes with other people.
And he was best known for dragging in people to see the apartment had he let their class go by themselves.
He just did not win any friends at all.
I was careful not to do that when my class was anywhere in vicinity of parks.
But he was very good to me.
And so I would remember him.
I would go to him for advice.
You know, when I'm thinking, except for Sylvia, these are all men.
Catherine O'Keefe is not here anymore.
She's in Notre Dame.
And I think that's about the list of people I would go to for advice.
Well, let's finish the questions and then we'll think.
I would want it for the establishment of an MFA program.
A million dollars wouldn't go far in that direction.
If I couldn't do that, then I wouldn't have speaker series, another instructor, whatever, in the area of doing writing.
since 1958.
I've been teaching here since 1969.
I taught elsewhere before and for one year during this time period.
But other than that, I know nothing.
I don't know how other institutions work.
And I certainly enjoyed teaching.
And I was
but other people from that time period.
And now I'm beginning to see, I've had the children of my first student.
I figure when the grandchildren show up, it's probably time to retire.
And so I would say in many ways I do identify with Texas a lot.
But I'm not a traditional student.
I'm just trying to think of things
